  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "Upload your own images to the **Asset Manager** and draw them in your scene!\r\n\r\n<details style=\"background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;\">\r\n    <summary style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;\">🔦 Where can I find images?</summary>\r\n    <div style=\"margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n\t\t<p>The following are some websites where you can find images. Images in The Theater are limited to a <strong>5 MB</strong> file size.</p>\r\n\r\n* <a href=\"https://unsplash.com/\" target=\"_blank\">**Unsplash**</a>\r\n\r\n* <a href=\"https://pixabay.com/\" target=\"_blank\">**pixabay**</a>\r\n\r\n* <a href=\"https://www.pexels.com/\" target=\"_blank\">**Pexels**</a>\r\n\r\n* <a href=\"https://www.freeimages.com/\" target=\"_blank\">**FreeImages**</a>\r\n\r\n* <a href=\"https://free-images.com/\" target=\"_blank\">**Free-Images.com**</a>\r\n    </div>\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ImageScene.java</code>, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">drawScene()</code> method to draw each image separately.\r\n\r\nYou can choose where you want to draw the images and the size of the images.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">TheaterRunner.java</code>,\r\n\r\n1. Declare separate <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">String</code> variables to store the names of the image files that you uploaded to the **Asset Manager**.\r\n\r\n2. Instantiate an <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">ImageScene</code> object with image file names.\r\n\r\n3. Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">drawScene()</code> method.\r\n\r\n⚠️ **Don't forget!** Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Theater.playScenes(yourSceneObject)</code> method to play the scene.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the documentation for the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Scene</code> class in the <strong>Documentation</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with drawing images in a scene.\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<details style=\"background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;\">\r\n    <summary style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;\">🔦 How can I animate the images?</summary>\r\n    <div style=\"margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n\t\t<p>Try using the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">pause()</code> or <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">clear()</code> methods to turn your scene into an animation!</p>\r\n\r\n* Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">pause()</code> method after drawing each image or after drawing a set of images.\r\n\r\n* Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">clear()</code> method to clear the scene before drawing another image if you don't want the previous image to still display in the scene.\r\n    </div>\r\n</details>",
    "mini_rubric": "false",
    "submittable": "false",
    "hide_share_and_remix": "false",
    "csa_view_mode": "theater",
    "start_sources": {
      "TheaterRunner.java": {
        "text": "import org.code.theater.*;\n\npublic class TheaterRunner {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n\n    /* ----------------------------------- TO DO -----------------------------------\n     * ✅ Declare individual variables for each image, then instantiate an\n     * ImageScene object with the images, then call the drawScene() method.\n     * -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n     */\n\n\n\n    \n    \n  }\n}",
        "isVisible": true,
        "tabOrder": 0
      },
      "ImageScene.java": {
        "text": "import org.code.theater.*;\n\n/*\n * Represents a scene of images\n */\npublic class ImageScene extends Scene {\n\n  private String image1;\n  private String image2;\n  private String image3;\n  private String image4;\n\n  /*\n   * Initializes the scene with each image file name\n   */\n  public ImageScene(String image1, String image2, String image3, String image4) {\n    this.image1 = image1;\n    this.image2 = image2;\n    this.image3 = image3;\n    this.image4 = image4;\n  }\n\n  /*\n   * Draws each image in the scene\n   */\n  public void drawScene() {\n    /* ----------------------------------- TO DO -----------------------------------\n     * ✅ Draw each image in the scene. You choose where you want to draw the \n     *    images and the size of the images.\n     * -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n     */\n\n\n    \n  }\n}\n",
        "isVisible": true,
        "tabOrder": 1
      }
    },
    "display_name": "Draw Your Own Images",
    "bubble_choice_description": "Upload your own images to the Asset Manager and draw them in your scene.",
